In [ ]:
# 1. the ID column could be drop as it will not affect our analysis.
# 2. Looking at the people age, it's prety clear that people less than 26 and older than 65 and not allowed to take loan.
# 3. The larger the income, the higher probability that the customer will take a loan.
# 4. It is clear that only specific ZIP codes (areas) are allowed to take loan.
# 5. Family of all sizes are allowed to take a loan but with a very low probability. Families of size 3 and 4 are most likely to take a loan than families of size 1 and 2.
# 6. The higher the educational level, the higher probability of taking a loan.
# 7. For the Mortgage, we cannot say that people with high mortgage cannot take loan as we have outliers and vise versa.
# 8. It is pretty clear, that the class column [personal loan] is unbalanced. and hence analyzing the data becomes more difficult.
# will work on balancing the data and will elaborate more on this point in step 6 where we will build the same model 
# on a balanced dataset and see how the accuracy and evaluation metrics will change.
# but for now, let's build the model with the data we have in hand so far.

# predict probabilities
lr_probs = model.predict_proba(X_test)
# keep probabilities for the positive outcome only
lr_probs = lr_probs[:, 1]
# calculate scores
lr_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, lr_probs)
# summarize scores
print('Logistic: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (lr_auc))
# calculate roc curves
lr_fpr, lr_tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, lr_probs)
# plot the roc curve for the model
pyplot.plot(lr_fpr, lr_tpr, marker='.', label='Logistic')
# axis labels
pyplot.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
pyplot.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
# show the legend
pyplot.legend()
# show the plot
pyplot.show()

#he is not harming the bank financial state or level, he can assume himself on the safe side. Yes, we are loosing the 
#trust of some customers, but gaining the trust of even much more customers.
